{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584156"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:39:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:39:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14410"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14410"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.65,0.09,0,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7105"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60242"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7105"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45662"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4905"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9858"},{"type":"tags","id":"9863"},{"type":"tags","id":"9864"},{"type":"tags","id":"9865"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17151"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60242"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a primary determinant of end-systolic volume?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Venous return","Afterload","Filling time","Heart rate","Ventricular compliance"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary determinants of end-systolic volume are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAfterload\u003C/strong\u003E (correct): This is the pressure against which the ventricle must contract to eject blood. Higher afterload increases end-systolic volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContractility: Increased contractility decreases end-systolic volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPreload: Higher preload can indirectly decrease end-systolic volume by increasing contractility via the Frank-Starling mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous return\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects end-diastolic volume rather than end-systolic volume. \u003Cstrong\u003EFilling time\u003C/strong\u003E is more related to diastolic function and end-diastolic volume. \u003Cstrong\u003EHeart rate\u003C/strong\u003E can indirectly affect end-systolic volume by altering filling time and contractility, but it is not a primary determinant. \u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular compliance\u003C/strong\u003E mainly influences end-diastolic volume and pressure-volume relationships, but does not directly determine end-systolic volume.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["End-systolic volume is primarily determined by afterload, contractility, and preload.","Afterload is the pressure against which the ventricle must contract to eject blood."],"references":["King J, Lowery DR. Physiology, Cardiac Output. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470455/","Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"ite